  "prompt": "Do anti-money laundering regulations exist?",
  "response": "Yes, anti-money laundering (AML) regulations exist in most countries. These regulations are designed to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income. Key elements typically include:\n\n1. Reporting requirements for financial institutions\n2. Customer identification procedures\n3. Monitoring of suspicious transactions\n4. Mandatory reporting of large cash transactions\n5. International cooperation to track and prevent money laundering\n\nIn the United States, the Bank Secrecy Act and the USA PATRIOT Act are primary AML regulatory frameworks. Other countries have similar laws, and there are also international standards set by organizations like the Financial Action Task Force (FATF).",
